Polyene polyketides, methods for their production and use as pharmaceuticals [Related Applications] This application is based on US Provisional Application No. 60 / 441,123, filed Jan. 21, 2003, and US Provisional Application No. 60 / 441,2003. Claims priority to 60 / 494,568, US provisional application 60 / 469,810 filed May 13, 2003 and US provisional application 60 / 491,516 filed August 1, 2003 Is.

Abstract
translated from Japanese


The present invention relates to a new class of polyene polyketides, pharmaceutically acceptable salts and derivatives thereof and methods for obtaining the compounds. One way to obtain these compounds is by culturing a new strain of Streptomyces isonensis, and another method involves the expression of genes in the biosynthetic pathway in transformed host cells. The present invention further provides novel strains of Streptomyces isenensis used to produce these compounds and the use of these compounds and their pharmaceutically acceptable salts and derivatives as drugs, particularly fungal cell growth and And its use as an inhibitor of cancer cell growth. The invention also relates to pharmaceutical compositions comprising these novel polyketides or their pharmaceutically acceptable salts or derivatives. Finally, the present invention relates to novel polynucleotide sequences involved in the biosynthesis of these novel polyketides and their encoded proteins.

Streptomyces aizunensis   The present invention relates to a new class of polyene polyketides, their pharmaceutically acceptable salts and derivatives, and methods for their production. One method for obtaining these novel polyketides is by culturing a new strain of Streptomyces aizunensis; another method is the biosynthetic gene of the invention in transformed host cells. It is related to the expression of clusters. Compounds are also produced by known strains of bacteria. The present invention encompasses novel strains of Streptomyces isuzunensis that produce these compounds and gene clusters that direct the biosynthesis of these compounds. The present invention relates to the use of these new polyketides and their pharmaceutically acceptable salts and pharmaceutical derivatives, in particular fungal and bacterial cell growth inhibitors, cancer cell growth inhibitors, and serum cholesterol and Has been used to lower other steroids. The present invention includes pharmaceutically acceptable compositions comprising these novel polyketides, or pharmaceutically acceptable salts or derivatives thereof.

family   Actinomycetes constitute a family of bacteria that are abundant in soil, and many of these therapeutically useful antibiotics, antifungals, anticancer agents and drugs that lower cholesterol are used by these bacteria. As a result of being produced as a secondary metabolite, it has provided tremendous commercial and scientific benefits. Many actinomycetes, especially the genus Streptomyces, have been extensively studied because they have the ability to produce a remarkably diverse bioactive metabolite. A thorough search for new natural products has led to the identification of new species and the creation of improved strains.

  Polyketides have a carbon chain backbone consisting of two carbon units formed through a series of condensation reactions and subsequent modifications. Type I polyketides are effectively synthesized by a modular polyketide synthase (PKS) enzyme with separate catalytic active sites for each cycle of carbon chain elongation and modification. Because PKS proteins have multi-modular properties, the specificity and mechanism of polyketide biosynthesis is well known.

  Despite the identification of many bioactive compounds, there remains a need to obtain new natural compounds with enhanced properties. Current methods of obtaining such compounds include costly and time consuming screening of natural isolates and chemical modification of existing compounds. Current screening methods are based on the general biological properties of compounds and require prior knowledge of the molecular structure. Although there are methods for chemically modifying known active compounds, there are substantial limitations as to the type of compound obtained.

II   The present invention is also directed to methods of producing compound 2 (a) and related compounds comprising Formula I and Formula II as defined herein. Such a method comprises culturing cells derived from a Streptomyces isuzunensis strain, aerobically incubating the cultured cells in a growth medium for a time similar to that required for production of the desired compound. Extracting the medium with a solvent such as methanol or ethanol and purifying the compound from the crude extract. The Streptomyces isenensis strain used in the method of the present invention may be NRRL B-11277 or a variant thereof. A preferred strain of Streptomyces isenensis useful in the methods of the present invention is the mutant strain identified as [C03] 023 (deposited accession number IDAC0700803-1). The most preferred strain of Streptomyces isuzunensis useful in the methods of the invention is the mutant strain identified as [C03U03] 023 (deposited accession number IDAC231203-02). The present invention also includes Streptomyces isenensis strains identified as deposit accession numbers IDAC0700803-1 and IDAC231203-02.

  Recombinant means that the nucleic acid coexists in a cell with a backbone nucleic acid that does not coexist in the natural environment. Recombinant is also defined to mean that the nucleic acid is adjacent to a backbone nucleic acid that is not adjacent in the natural environment. A concentrated nucleic acid indicates that there are 5% or more nucleic acid inserts in the nucleic acid backbone molecule group. Backbone molecules include nucleic acids such as expression vectors, self-replicating nucleic acids, viruses, integrated nucleic acids, and other vectors or nucleic acids used to maintain or manipulate the nucleic acid of interest. The concentrated nucleic acid is preferably 15% or more of the total number of nucleic acid inserts present in the recombinant backbone molecule group, more preferably 50% or more, and most preferably 90% or more.

  Recombinant polypeptide or protein refers to a polypeptide or protein made by a recombinant DNA technique, ie, made from a cell transformed with a foreign DNA construct encoding the polypeptide or protein of interest. . A synthetic polypeptide or protein is a polypeptide or protein prepared by chemical synthesis.

  The expression gene refers to a segment of DNA involved in the production of a polypeptide chain, the region before and after the coding region (leader and trailer) and, if applicable, intervening between individual coding segments (exons) Contains a region (intron).

Genetic modification of gene sites, gene clusters, or biosynthetic sites refers to any genetic recombination technique known in the art, and can be applied to create nucleic acid variants that can be applied to create variants of compounds of formula I. Includes mutagenesis, inactivation, or substitution.

  Digestion of DNA refers to the enzymatic cleavage of DNA with a restriction enzyme that causes only certain sequences to act on the DNA. The various restriction enzymes used here are commercially available and their reaction status, cofactors, and other requirements were used as known to those skilled in the art. For analysis, typically 1 g of plasmid or DNA fragment is used with 20 units of buffer solution along with the unit enzyme. For the purpose of isolating DNA fragments to construct a plasmid, typically 5-50 g of DNA is digested with a larger volume of 20-250 units of enzyme. Appropriate buffers and substrate amounts for particular enzymes are specified by the manufacturer. Typically, a 1 hour incubation time at 37 C. is used, but may vary depending on the supplier's instructions. After digestion, gel electrophoresis may be performed to isolate the desired fragment.

As an example of nucleic acid hybridization, a polymer membrane containing immobilized denatured nucleic acid is first prepared with 0.9 M NaCl, 50 mM NaH 2 PO 4 , pH 7.0, 5.0 mM Na 2 EDTA, 0.5% SDS. Next, 32 P-end-labeled oligonucleotide probes of about 2 10 7 cpm (specific activity 4~9 10 8 cpm / ug) , it is added to the solution. After 12-16 hours of culture, the membrane was washed with 1 SET (150 mM NaCl, 20 mM Tris hydrochloride, pH 7.8, 1 mM Na 2 EDTA) containing 0.5% SDS for 30 minutes at room temperature. The membrane is then exposed to autoradiographic film in order to detect the hybridization signal.

  Nucleic acids with different levels of homology to the probe are identified by changing the stringency of the hybridization conditions used to identify nucleic acids such as genomic DNA or cDNA that hybridize to the detectable probe. It can be isolated. By performing the hybridization at various temperatures below the melting temperature of the probe, the stringency is changed. The melting temperature of the probe can be calculated using the following formula:

  For oligonucleotide probes 14 to 70 nucleotides in length, the melting temperature (Tm) (Celsius) is given by the formula: Tm = 81.5 + 16.6 (log [Na +]) + 0.41 (fraction G + C) (600 / N) Can be used to calculate. Here, N is the length of the oligonucleotide.

  When hybridization is performed in a solution containing formamide, the melting temperature is the equation: Melting temperature = 81.5 + 16.6 (log [Na +]) + 0.41 (fraction G + C) (0.63% formamide) -600 / N). Here, N is the length of the probe.

Sambrook et al.   Prehybridization consists of 6 SSC, 5 Denhart reagent, 0.5% SDS, 0.1 mg / ml denatured and fragmented salmon sperm DNA or 6 SSC, 5 Denhart reagent, 0.5% SDS , 0.1 mg / ml denatured and fragmented salmon sperm DNA, 50% formamide. SSC compositions and Denhardt's solutions are listed in Sambrook et al., Supra.

  Hybridization is performed by adding a detectable probe to the hybridization solution listed above. The site where the probe constitutes double-stranded DNA is denatured by culturing at high temperature and quickly cooling before adding to the hybridization solution. In order to eliminate or reduce the formation of secondary structures or oligomers, it is desirable to denature single-stranded probes as well. The filter is contacted with the hybridization solution for a sufficient period of time so that the probe can hybridize to cDNA or genomic DNA containing complementary or homologous sequences. For probes having nucleotides longer than 200, hybridization is performed at 15-25 C. below the melting temperature. For shorter probes, such as oligonucleotide probes, hybridization is performed at a temperature 5-10 C. below the melting temperature. Preferably, for shorter probes, hybridization is performed at 6 SSC. Preferably, hybridization is performed in 50% formamide containing a solution for longer probes. All of the above hybridizations are considered examples of hybridization performed under high stringency conditions.

  Following hybridization, the filter is washed for at least 15 minutes with 2 SSC, 0.1% SDS at room temperature or higher at the desired stringency. The filter is then washed with 0.1 SSC, 0.5% SDS (again) at room temperature for 30 minutes to 1 hour. Nucleic acids hybridized to the probe are identified by conventional autoradiography and non-radioactive detection methods.

  The above procedure may be modified to identify nucleic acids with reduced levels of homology to the probe sequence. For example, lower stringency conditions are used to obtain nucleic acids with reduced homology to detectable probes. For example, in a hybridization buffer having a Na + concentration of about 1M, the hybridization temperature is decreased by 5 C. from 68 C. to 42 C. Following hybridization, the filter is washed with 2 SSC, 0.5% SDS at the hybridization temperature. These conditions are considered moderate stringency above 50 C. and low stringency conditions below 50 C. A specific example of moderate stringency hybridization conditions is when the above hybridization is performed at 55 C. A specific example of low stringency hybridization conditions is when the above hybridization is carried out at 45 C.

  Alternatively, hybridization is performed in a buffer such as 6 SSC containing formamide at a temperature of 42 C. In this case, to identify clones with reduced levels of homology to the probe, the concentration of formamide in the hybridization buffer is decreased by 5% from 50% to 0%. Following hybridization, the filter is washed with 6 SSC, 0.5% SDS at 50 C. These conditions are considered to be moderate stringency conditions with 25% or more formamide and low stringency conditions with 25% or less formamide. A specific example of moderate stringency hybridization conditions is when the above hybridization is carried out with 30% formamide. A specific example of low stringency hybridization conditions is when the above hybridization is carried out with 10% formamide. Nucleic acids hybridized to the probe are identified by conventional autoradiography and non-radioactive detection methods.

sequential manner[Hopwood, Chem. Rev., 97: 24, 65-24, 97 (1997) ]   The biosynthesis of compound 2 (a) is the multi-modular type I polyketide synthase system of ORF 10-18 (SEQ ID NO: 21, 23, 25, 27, 29, 31, 33, 35 and 37) shown in FIG. PKS). Type I PKS is a large modular protein that condenses acylthioesters in a sequential manner. The PKS system is composed of one or more multifunctional polypeptides, each of which is composed of modules. Each type I PKS module has three domains: -ketoacyl protein synthase (KS), acyltransferase (AT) and acyl carrier protein (ACP). Domains that confer additional enzymatic activity such as ketoreductase (KR), dehydratase (DH) and enoyl reductase (ER) are also found in the PKS module. These additional domains reduce the -keto group of the extending polyketide chain at various levels. Each module is responsible for a single condensation and reduction of -ketoacyl units. There is a direct correlation not only between the number of modules and the length of the polyketide chain, but also between the domain composition of the module and the level of polyketide product reduction. The final polyketide product is released from the PKS protein by the action of the thioesterase domain found in the final module of the PKS system. The genetic makeup of most type I PKS enzymes is aligned with the sequence of biochemical reactions that produce the polyketide chain. One skilled in the art will readily appreciate that these features allow prediction of the polyketide nuclear structure based on the construction of the PKS module found in a given biosynthetic pathway. [Hopwood, Chem. Rev., 97: 24, 65-24, 97 (1997)].

  The PKS system for the Compound 2 (a) site is composed of ORFs 10-18 (SEQ ID NOs: 21, 23, 25, 27, 29, 31, 33, 35 and 37) and totaled as shown in Table 3. It has 27 modules. The first module includes only the ACP domain and corresponds to the additional module (module 0). On the other hand, the remaining 26 modules contain KS, AT and ACP domains in various combinations with KR, DH and ER domains. The thioesterase domain present in ORF18 / module 26 indicates that this module is the final module in polyketide chain biosynthesis. The dehydratase domain in modules 6 and 11 and the ketoreductase domain in module 12 are inactive because there are non-conserved amino acid residues in highly conserved regions important for catalysis.

Production of Compound 2 (a) by Fermentation [Example 1 (A)]
Generation of [C03U03] 023 strain [C03] 023 strain Streptomyces isuzunensis NRRLB-11277 was seeded on three tomato paste oatmeal agar (ATCC medium 1360) plates at 28 C. for sporulation. The plates were incubated for a period of 5-7 days, after which the spores were collected from each plate in 5 ml of sterile distilled water, sedimented by centrifugation at 5000 rpm (10 minutes) and dispersed in 20 ml of sterile water. . After a second centrifugation under similar conditions, the pellet was resuspended in 10 ml of sterile water. A series of 10-fold dilutions of the original spore suspension was prepared and 0.5 ml aliquots were plated on tomato paste oatmeal agar until spore formation occurred (5-7 days). Individual clones derived from plates with well-isolated colonies alone (produced from a 10 8 to 10 10 dilution of spore suspension) are selected and tomatoes produced to produce preserved spores Moved to one plate of paste oatmeal agar. Each clone was grown in a 25 150 mm glass for the production of compound 2 (a). A total of 385 clones were examined for compound 2 (a) production levels. Clone [03] 023 was generated 3 times compared to the wild type strain. This clone was selected, stored and used for mutagenesis.


baffledL [C03U03] 023 strain The aqueous spore suspension of [C03] 023 was mutated by UV irradiation (254 nm) at different energy levels (expressed in mJoules per surface area). The clone [C03U03] 023 obtained at 0.4 mJ / 1 cm 2 showed slightly more production than the parent clone [C03] 023. The production of compound 2 (a) by the new clone is always reproducible in both shake flasks (500 ml medium QB or 2L-baffled flask VA) and 100-L fermentor with medium VA. .



[Example 1 (B)]
Activation of lyophilized sample of [C03U03] 023 strain [C03U03] 023 strain was provided as a lyophilized pellet. The lyophilized sample was opened aseptically and 0.3-0.5 ml of ITSB medium was added to the sample to make a cell suspension. To form a liquid culture, the cell suspension was transferred to 25 ml of ITSB medium (described below) in a 125 ml flask. Liquid cultures were incubated at 28 C. for 3-5 days until visible growth occurred. Culture purity was checked by streaking the loop on an ISP2 agar plate.



[Example 1 (C)]
Preparation and Storage of [C03U03] 023 Glycerol Stock The [C03U03] 023 strain was grown on several tomato paste oatmeal agar plates at 28 C. for 7 days to 10 days. Surface growth was collected from each plate in sterile distilled water, sedimented by centrifugation at 5000 rpm (10 minutes), and dispersed in 10 ml of sterile water. After a second centrifugation under similar conditions, the pellets were resuspended in 2 ml of sterile glycol 25% and 0.5 ml aliquots were stored at 80 C. in screw cap glass bottles. In addition to the glycerol stock, the recovered cell mass was resuspended in 15% sterile nonfat dry milk and 0.5 ml aliquots were dispensed into glass ampoules and lyophilized according to standard methods.



[Example 1 (D)]
Preparation of seed cultures Vials containing frozen mycelia prepared as described in Example 1 (C) were removed from the freezer and stored on dry ice. Under aseptic conditions, a loopful frozen culture was taken, streaked on the surface of a tomato paste oatmeal agar plate, and incubated at 28 C. until proliferating cells appeared (5-7 days). To initiate seed culture, surface growth from tomato paste oatmeal agar plates was transferred to a 1.5 ml Eppendorf tube containing 300 l ITSB medium. The mycelium with agar fragments was homogenized and 1 ml of ITSB medium was added to the suspension. The contents were used to inoculate two 125 ml flasks containing 25 ml of sterile medium. The flask was incubated at 28 C. for 65-70 hours on a 250 rpm rotary shaker. This seed culture was used to seed the production medium QB or VA.



[Example 1 (E)]
Production of Compound 2 (a) by Fermentation The seed culture sample prepared as described in Example 1 (D) above was checked for contamination by a microscope. The seed culture samples were then streaked into one ISP2 plate (control plate) and incubated at 28 C. 10 ml from a sterile seed culture was taken and used to incubate each 2 liter controlled flask containing 500 ml medium-free QB or VA. The fermented batch was incubated aerobically with shaking (250 rpm) at 28 C. for 7 days. After incubation for 3-5 days, the culture purity of the control plate was examined.

Ried et. al. Biochemistry, 2003, 42:7279; Udo et. al., Biochemistry, 1997, 36:3440   At the compound 2 (a) locus, the KR domain present in ORF13, module 12, is inactive. To yield the compound of Example 7, the KR domain is reactivated or replaced with an active KR domain. Reactivation of the KR domain requires a diagnosis of the integrity of key active site residues required for functional KR domains. Active site residues can be divided into those required for KR enzyme coenzyme activation and those required for catalysis. Experiments to identify specific residues for ketoreductase activity (Ried et. Al. Biochemistry, 2003, 42: 72-79; Udo et. Al., Biochemistry, 1997, 36: 34-40) KR coenzyme binding site residues include glycine (G), glycine (G), glycine (G), alanine (A), and functional KR active site residues include serine (S), tyrosine (Y), And asparagine (N). These residues are highlighted in FIGS. 6a and 6b. The KR domain sequence at the Compound 2 (a) locus shows that the coenzyme active site residue is glycine (G), glycine (G), glycine (G), alanine (which indicates that this site is indeed active). A). However, the amino acid residues found at the KR site responsible for catalytic activity are serine (S), glutamine (Q) and asparagine (N), indicating that the catalytic site is probably inactive. This finding is confirmed by the fact that compound 2 (a) contains a carbonyl group at that particular position (FIG. 10, module 12). Modification of the codon encoding glutamine to a codon encoding tyrosine results in the active site residues necessary for functional keto reduction of the PKS monomer. This is a modification of the locus of compound 2 (a) used to modify the appropriate host cell to produce compound 2 (a) mutant of Example 7, as shown in FIG. 12a. The result is a nucleic acid sequence.

The characteristics of hypocholesterolemia due to polyene compounds were first revealed in a dog study (Schaffner, C.P. and Gordon H.W. The Hypocholesterolemic activity of orally administered polyene macrolides. P.N.A.S. 61: 36-41, 1968.). In another study using birds, small amounts of polyene compounds in the diet induced inhibition of enterohepatic cholesterol circulation, increased fecal lipid excretion, and decreased atherogenesis (Fisher, H., Griminger P. and Siller W. Effect of candicidin on plasma cholesterol and avian atherosclerosis. Proceedings of the Society for Experimental Biology and Medicine, 145: 836-839, 1974). The beneficial effect of orally administered polyene compounds on cholesterol lipid metabolism is not species-dependent, as shown in several species such as humans, rats, dogs and birds (Pagliano FM, Correction of hyperdyslipidemia).
